In perfect harmony: award-winning pianist Benjamin Grosvenor and his brother Jonathan Benjamin Grosvenor reveals why he chose to dedicate his Classic Brits Critics' Choice award to his Down's syndrome brother Jonathan
'He’s grown to appreciate the nice food and the beer': Jonathan and Benjamin Grosvenor Photo: FIONA HANSON	By Julia Llewellyn Smith
7:30AM BST 07 Oct 2012
Follow Comments
Traditionally, awards-ceremony speeches are gushy, dull and overlong, but on Tuesday night, when Benjamin Grosvenor accepted the coveted Critic’s Choice award at the Classic Brits, the audience was genuinely moved. “I dedicated it to my brother, Jonathan,” says the 20-year-old pianist, whom critics are calling our most important musical talent in decades. “It was for putting up with my incessant practice over the years and coming to so many of my concerts against his will.”
Jonathan, 22, who has Down’s syndrome and is visually impaired, responded by standing up and excitedly displaying his place-card to the audience. Does he think his brother is famous now? “Yes,” he grins. “Well…” Benjamin responds, laughing. “Some people came up to my parents on the red carpet and complained: 'There’s no one famous here!’ But then Jonathan and Charlotte – I think they’re brother and sister from Britain’s Got Talent – arrived. People were shouting 'Jonathan, come and sign my autograph book!’ and Jono thought they were talking to him…”
“But I don’t know how to sign an autograph,” says Jonathan, beside him, at the dining table in the Thirties-style semi in Southend, where the brothers still live with their teacher parents. Related Articles
