“You just write your name, Jono,” says Benjamin fondly. This was Benjamin’s second awards-ceremony experience in a week. A few days previously, he won two Gramophone Awards: the instrumental category and Young Artist of the Year. An endearingly unworldly young man, Benjamin’s sudden immersion into popular culture has been unnerving. “Yes, it’s been a bit of a strange experience for me,” he says. “There was an after-party in a club. It was a small room and then all the Military Wives arrived and it was very crowded and noisy, difficult to talk. I’m not really a fan of those things, though Gareth Malone [choirmaster from The Choir] did say he liked my speech. He seems very nice.”
In jeans and a T-shirt, with a shock of mad-professor hair, Benjamin comes across as slightly old-fashioned, with a keen a sense of irony. In person, especially compared to the more extrovert Jonathan, he is stiff-upper-lipped. The emotions express themselves in his piano playing. Probably because Benjamin is the youngest of five boys, there is none of the arrogance occasionally associated with prodigies. In 2004, as a chubby-cheeked 11-year-old, he reached the final of the BBC Young Musician of the Year, his hands still unable to span an octave. At the time, there were snide murmurs about pushy parents and inevitable burnout. But nearly a decade later, Benjamin is vindicated. Last year he became the first British pianist in 60 years to sign with the prestigious Decca label, and the youngest soloist at First Night of the Proms. His Critic’s Choice award for his debut Decca CD, Chopin Liszt Ravel, beat prestigious nominees such as Sir Simon Rattle and the Berlin Philharmonic. “Yeah, things are going quite well at the moment.” Benjamin frowns slightly. “I’m just not used to all the attention. “I have no ambitions,” he continues. “When I was very young my ideal was to play at the Albert Hall with the Royal Philharmonic, but I was lucky enough to do that at 13.”
Benjamin began playing aged five, a pupil of his piano-teacher mother, Rebecca. “All my brothers had learnt instruments and were quite good, but they gave up in their early teens. I persevered.”
Initially, he claims to have been an average student, but at eight, he suddenly took off. “There was a Chopin waltz [Grade-8 standard] that I learnt very quickly apparently and seemed to have an emotional understanding of.”
At 14, he was taken out of grammar school to study for A- levels at home, fitting schoolwork around practising on his second-hand Bösendorfer bought with a £10,000 loan from his grandmother and £17,000 from his own earnings. The instrument may have been distinguished, but the neighbours were distinctly unimpressed. “We moved the piano to the other side of the room and a few years ago we put boxes of my CDS in front of the fireplace, stuffing the empty ones with paper. Amateur soundproofing. We haven’t had complaints since.”
Until last year, when the last of the three elder brothers moved out, he and Jonathan had to share a bedroom. “Jono has a tendency to snore, so I do have more restful nights now,” he says. Jonathan in turn is glad not to be kept up by his brother reading musical theory books. As children, the boys played together all the time. “I don’t think of him as having Down’s syndrome any more. To me, his main disability is his sight.” Jonathan has a cataract that wasn’t treated as a baby. “He finds it infuriating, and I think it’s this that holds him back more than anything else.”
Jonathan has travelled round the world to watch his brother play. “He had no choice, there was no one at home to look after him. I don’t think he enjoys concerts, though there are certain pieces like Gershwin’s I Got Rhythm where he stands and cheers at the end. And he’s grown to appreciate the nice food and more recently the beer he might get in the pub afterwards.”
“I like your concerts,” says Jonathan. “You don’t need to lie so as not to hurt my feelings,” Benjamin says gently. Jonathan recalls one grudge. “I gave up time on my birthday to go to a different country with you.”
“You went up the Empire State Building. Isn’t that a good way to spend a birthday?”
“Usually, I spend time with my friend Paul on my birthday,” Jonathan replies firmly. Jonathan enjoys pop music, especially Westlife. “Those modulations at the end of the songs!” Benjamin says despairingly of his brother’s taste. In contrast, pop has passed Grosvenor by. “Though I did use to love Queen. They did things that were musically interesting”. He has close friends from the Royal Academy of Music, from which he graduated in the summer, but there’s no time for romance (asked about groupies, he quipped that they tended to be over 60). Driving lessons start soon, but for now Mum is his chauffeur, ferrying him and Jonathan all over Europe, to non-stop performances. He’s in no hurry to fly the nest. “One day. But I’ll have to find a place with neighbours who don’t mind practising.”
He admits to being a perfectionist, who is often stressed. In contrast, Jonathan is happy-go-lucky. When Benjamin gets frustrated, he ends up clowning around with Jonathan to let off steam. “When I go away without him, he’s the person I miss the most, because he brings so much joy.”
'The Classic Brits’ will be shown on ITV tonight at 10.20pm. Grosvenor makes his Southbank debut in the International Piano Series on October 31 Music
