My Property Nightmare
Robbed of privacy
Mary Wilson
12:01AM BST 20 Jul 2005
Comments
Bryan Chittenden has lived peacefully in his bungalow in Tunbridge Wells, Kent, for 16 years. But on April 1 this year, planning permission was granted for two four-bedroom houses at the bottom of his garden, writes Mary Wilson
"The bedroom windows in one house will look right over my bungalow," he says. "My other neighbour will be overlooked by both houses." Bryan was unaware of the proposals until it was too late to object. He discovered that a letter about the plans had been sent to him, but the Royal Mail returned it because it did not bear his full address. It wasn't until April 5 that he saw the plans and that a magnificent 60ft copper beech tree at the bottom of his garden - which had been subject to a tree preservation order since 1977 - had been omitted. There were details of how smaller trees on the site would be preserved, and one larger tree felled, but nothing about the copper beech. He pointed out the omission to a planning officer at Wealden District Council. "The foundations of one house will be about 43ft from the centre of the trunk - 6½ft closer than the Subsidence Claims Advisory Bureau recommends," Bryan says. "Also a proportion of the tree will need to be lopped off so that the house can be built. This could destabilise the tree, as could the foundations." Bryan is also concerned that the tree will still be 13ft taller than the house. "It will not be very good for future neighbourly relations. If we had a bad gale, it could be blown down. Or a branch could break off and damage the roof," he says. "These two new houses will, undoubtedly, affect the tree and will definitely affect me. However, the official said that as planning consent had been given, nothing could be done." A spokesman for Wealden District Council comments: "Outline permission was granted in 2000. When approving the development's layout, as part of discussions for detailed permission, planning officers were able to ensure that none of the five existing trees on the site had to be removed. The beech tree protected by a TPO (tree perservation order) will require a limited amount of pruning to accommodate the roof of the garage. We intend to monitor this work closely. Before any work begins, the developer must satisfy the council that the correct fencing is in place to protect the trees."
David Henry, a planning director for Savills (01223 347000), comments: "The granting of planning permission overrides the TPO. However, a TPO is a strong material consideration in determining a planning application, whether at outline stage or later. The decision-makers should give significant weight to protection of the tree when looking at the plans. Even if it was not shown, the council's records should have shown it up. So it is worth checking that this was the case - if not, there may be negligence and thus a case for the Ombudsman. "The outline consent in 2000 merely established the principle of developing the site. Important details such as the layout and design of the properties are not foregone conclusions. The amenity of neighbours is an important factor in this - and not one to be overlooked lightly. "Lack of neighbour notification is administratively lax. Once the letter to Mr Chittenden was returned to them, it was up to the council to figure out why. After all, they must have known the house was there, or else they wouldn't have sent the letter in the first place. This is another possible Ombudsman matter. "Finally, conditions are there to be abided by. Unfortunately, councils have few resources with which to police them. Mr Chittenden is their best watchdog. It may be worth him employing an arboriculturalist to monitor progress. Guidelines are only rules of thumb and the actual site conditions will have a significant effect on the health of the tree." Send your property stories to House & Home, The Sunday Telegraph, 1 Canada Square, Canary Wharf, London E14 5DT; or e-mail houseandhome@telegraph.co.uk
